1
00:00:00,210 --> 00:00:25,150
Good morning. It's good to be, to share the word again this morning. I encourage you, as Betty shared this morning, to be part of our prayer ministry this fall. As you know, we planned this out months ago, but the timing is just impeccable that we pray for our church, for our people, and for our nation. We look forward to your participation in that. It will be a blessed fall as we do that.

2
00:00:25,850 --> 00:00:30,970
Well, our national leaders say we need to continue to move on in the light of the tragedy that's come upon us

3
00:00:30,970 --> 00:00:33,290
and to live our lives and continue, and I agree.

4
00:00:33,810 --> 00:00:37,830
And I think it's time to resume again our experience and our sermon series

5
00:00:37,830 --> 00:00:40,190
and continue forward as we live our lives.

6
00:00:40,430 --> 00:00:43,010
We continue to mourn and struggle with the things around us,

7
00:00:43,010 --> 00:00:47,270
but we also need to continue to fill our minds and our hearts with the things of God and move on.

8
00:00:47,710 --> 00:00:51,290
And so we're going to begin and kind of resume our sermon series this morning.

9
00:00:51,390 --> 00:00:55,260
We started a couple weeks ago, and now we begin our second week.

10
00:00:55,560 --> 00:00:58,840
in a series on tough questions and honest answers.

11
00:00:59,640 --> 00:01:02,240
I'm pulling from Lee Strobel's book, The Case for Faith,

12
00:01:02,380 --> 00:01:04,400
and I encourage you, if you're so inclined,

13
00:01:04,480 --> 00:01:06,660
to get a hold of that and to read it and kind of study ahead.

14
00:01:06,880 --> 00:01:08,540
We're going to go through chapter by chapter,

15
00:01:09,100 --> 00:01:11,000
and we're going to be augmenting that material,

16
00:01:11,120 --> 00:01:13,240
but I look forward to sharing this with you.

17
00:01:15,440 --> 00:01:16,900
Psalm 105, it says,

18
00:01:16,900 --> 00:01:19,700
Give thanks to the Lord and proclaim His greatness.

19
00:01:20,540 --> 00:01:23,280
Let the whole world know what He has done.

20
00:01:23,720 --> 00:01:25,700
Sing to Him, yes, sing His praises.

21
00:01:25,700 --> 00:01:29,580
tell everyone about his miracles.

22
00:01:30,400 --> 00:01:33,540
Tell about the miracles of the Lord, says the Bible.

23
00:01:35,400 --> 00:01:37,960
Well, let me share as we begin this topic this morning

24
00:01:37,960 --> 00:01:41,260
what others have said about this issue of miracles.

25
00:01:41,940 --> 00:01:45,720
Richard Dawkins, famous atheist, said these words,

26
00:01:46,140 --> 00:01:50,340
the virgin birth, the resurrection, the raising of Lazarus,

27
00:01:50,420 --> 00:01:51,880
even the Old Testament miracles,

28
00:01:52,060 --> 00:01:55,440
all are freely used for religious propaganda.

29
00:01:55,440 --> 00:02:00,740
and they are very effective with an audience of unsophisticates and children.

30
00:02:02,370 --> 00:02:03,370
That's a bold statement.

31
00:02:05,170 --> 00:02:08,930
He's saying if you believe in the Old Testament miracles, New Testament miracles,

32
00:02:09,230 --> 00:02:12,490
you are unsophisticated and childlike in your intellectual capacity.

33
00:02:13,450 --> 00:02:14,250
Strong statement.

34
00:02:15,130 --> 00:02:18,330
Gary Habermas says something different.

35
00:02:19,110 --> 00:02:19,750
He writes,

36
00:02:19,930 --> 00:02:23,450
It is not just a provocative rumor that God has acted in history,

37
00:02:24,030 --> 00:02:26,290
but a fact worthy of our intellectual conviction.

38
00:02:27,160 --> 00:02:30,480
The miracles of Christianity are not an embarrassment to the Christian worldview.

39
00:02:30,480 --> 00:02:38,100
Rather, they are a testimony to the compassion of God for human beings benighted by sin and circumstance.

40
00:02:39,100 --> 00:02:43,180
Again, two conflicting views about the topic today.

41
00:02:44,300 --> 00:02:47,800
I'd like to begin this with just asking, well, what is the issue?

42
00:02:48,420 --> 00:02:51,340
What is the primary concern that we're going to address this morning

43
00:02:51,340 --> 00:02:56,180
as we seek to be people that can share and defend the Christian worldview

44
00:02:56,180 --> 00:03:03,380
in the face of tough intellectual questions posed by yourself or from friends or from family.

45
00:03:03,520 --> 00:03:04,180
What's the issue?

46
00:03:04,480 --> 00:03:06,920
Here's how it comes down in one simple phrase.

47
00:03:07,480 --> 00:03:14,360
Can one be scientifically sophisticated and still believe in miracles?

48
00:03:15,650 --> 00:03:16,330
That's the question.

49
00:03:17,600 --> 00:03:20,580
Can you be a contemporary, sophisticated individual

50
00:03:20,580 --> 00:03:24,040
that understands science and runs in those circles?

51
00:03:24,220 --> 00:03:31,420
Can you hold that position and still believe in the miracles in Scripture and today?

52
00:03:32,360 --> 00:03:35,440
The reality is many people have abandoned their faith in God

53
00:03:35,440 --> 00:03:39,220
because they could not reconcile the supposed tension

54
00:03:39,220 --> 00:03:42,780
between the God of the Bible and the tenets of modern science.

55
00:03:42,780 --> 00:03:46,760
They have been unable, for different reasons, to bring those two together.

56
00:03:46,840 --> 00:03:50,170
and they have sided with contemporary science

57
00:03:50,170 --> 00:03:53,730
and left God in the past or in the dust.

58
00:03:55,950 --> 00:03:57,990
And from that position, they believe then

59
00:03:57,990 --> 00:04:01,190
that the scripture is full of myth and story

60
00:04:01,190 --> 00:04:03,070
and fable and legend

61
00:04:03,070 --> 00:04:06,770
and that all the miracles and supernatural events

62
00:04:06,770 --> 00:04:09,290
are simply figments of imagination

63
00:04:09,290 --> 00:04:10,870
to communicate an idea

64
00:04:10,870 --> 00:04:14,170
but do not have any reality in history.

65
00:04:15,130 --> 00:04:17,270
Friends, there's a lot at stake with this issue

66
00:04:17,270 --> 00:04:20,660
about miracles and our contemporary worldview.

67
00:04:21,100 --> 00:04:23,680
So the question is, well, what then really is a miracle?

68
00:04:23,760 --> 00:04:25,380
We've got to make some definitions here.

69
00:04:25,720 --> 00:04:29,080
And I looked at the Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy as a place to go,

70
00:04:29,360 --> 00:04:31,040
and I found this definition of miracle.

71
00:04:31,040 --> 00:04:36,600
A miracle is a supernaturally, in parenthesis, divinely caused event,

72
00:04:37,220 --> 00:04:39,860
an event ordinarily different from what would have occurred

73
00:04:39,860 --> 00:04:42,780
in the normal or natural course of events.

74
00:04:44,010 --> 00:04:49,330
They summarize, it is a divine overriding of or an interference with the natural order.

75
00:04:50,340 --> 00:04:54,950
Dr. William Lane Craig, in the book, defines a miracle this way.

76
00:04:56,060 --> 00:05:03,560
An event which is not producible by the natural causes that are operative at the time and place that the event occurs.

77
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:08,020
Now we're going to unpack those and begin to really wrestle with what are the implications of that.

78
00:05:08,020 --> 00:05:11,080
But I want you to understand the gravity of this issue.

79
00:05:11,080 --> 00:05:17,940
I'm going to share with you some scriptures that clearly define or explain or show a miracle.

80
00:05:18,880 --> 00:05:23,180
And I want us to understand that if we cannot reconcile these, we must throw these out.

81
00:05:23,920 --> 00:05:26,180
1 Kings chapter 18, the Bible says,

82
00:05:27,230 --> 00:05:33,970
At the customary time for offering the evening sacrifice, Elijah the prophet walked up to the altar and prayed,

83
00:05:34,230 --> 00:05:40,690
O Lord God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, prove today that you are God in Israel and that I am your servant.

84
00:05:41,150 --> 00:05:43,930
Prove that I have done all of this at your command.

85
00:05:44,770 --> 00:05:45,770
O Lord, answer me.

86
00:05:46,700 --> 00:05:49,980
Answer me so these people will know that you, O Lord, are God

87
00:05:49,980 --> 00:05:52,300
and that you have brought them back to yourself.

88
00:05:53,820 --> 00:05:56,980
Immediately the fire of the Lord flashed down from heaven

89
00:05:56,980 --> 00:06:01,220
and burned up the young bull, the wood, the stones, and the dust.

90
00:06:01,820 --> 00:06:04,360
It even licked up all the water in the ditch.

91
00:06:04,360 --> 00:06:08,060
And when the people saw it, they fell on their faces and cried out,

92
00:06:08,060 --> 00:06:21,620
the Lord is God. The Lord is God. Amazing scenario. Can we believe it? In Luke chapter 5,

93
00:06:23,560 --> 00:06:29,080
this is told from scripture. One day while Jesus was teaching, some Pharisees and teachers of the

94
00:06:29,080 --> 00:06:34,740
law were sitting nearby. It seemed that these men showed up from every village in all of Galilee and

95
00:06:34,740 --> 00:06:40,660
Judea as well as from Jerusalem. And the Lord's healing power was strongly with Jesus. And some

96
00:06:40,660 --> 00:06:45,360
men carrying a paralyzed man a sleeping mat. They tried to push through the crowd to Jesus,

97
00:06:45,480 --> 00:06:50,100
but they couldn't reach him. So they went up on the roof, took off some tiles, and lowered

98
00:06:50,100 --> 00:06:56,170
the sick man down into the crowd still on his mat, right in front of Jesus. And seeing

99
00:06:56,170 --> 00:07:03,730
their faith, Jesus said to the man, Son, your sins are forgiven. Who does this man

100
00:07:03,730 --> 00:07:09,490
think he is? The Pharisees and teachers of religious law said to each other, This is

101
00:07:09,490 --> 00:07:16,210
blasphemy. Who but God can forgive them, can forgive sin? And Jesus knew what they were

102
00:07:16,210 --> 00:07:21,890
thinking, so he asked them, why do you think this is blasphemy? Is it easier to say your sins are

103
00:07:21,890 --> 00:07:29,020
forgiven, or get up and walk? I will prove that I, the Son of Man, have the authority on earth to

104
00:07:29,020 --> 00:07:35,600
forgive sin. Then Jesus turned to the paralyzed man and said, stand up, take your mat, and go on

105
00:07:35,600 --> 00:07:42,260
home because you are healed. And immediately, as everyone watched, the man jumped to his feet,

106
00:07:42,900 --> 00:07:48,860
picked up his mat, and went home praising God. And everyone was gripped with great wonder and awe,

107
00:07:48,860 --> 00:07:58,330
and they praised God, saying over and over again, we have seen amazing things today. Is it true?

108
00:08:02,130 --> 00:08:06,270
And probably the most important miracle of the scriptures. I'm going to read this one as well.

109
00:08:06,770 --> 00:08:13,600
You can follow along with me from Luke chapter 24. But very early on Sunday morning,

110
00:08:13,860 --> 00:08:19,410
The women came to the tomb, taking the spices they had prepared, and they found the stone

111
00:08:19,410 --> 00:08:23,950
covering the entrance had been rolled aside. So they went in, but they couldn't find the body

112
00:08:23,950 --> 00:08:29,900
of the Lord Jesus. They were puzzled, trying to think what could have happened to it.

113
00:08:30,340 --> 00:08:36,000
And suddenly the two men appeared to them clothed in dazzling robes. The women were terrified and

114
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:41,830
bowed low before them. Then the men asked, why are you looking in a tomb for someone who is alive?

115
00:08:42,370 --> 00:08:43,130
He isn't here.

116
00:08:43,490 --> 00:08:45,370
He has risen from the dead.

117
00:08:46,570 --> 00:08:48,810
Don't you remember what he told you back in Galilee?

118
00:08:49,130 --> 00:08:53,430
That the Son of Man must be betrayed into the hands of sinful men and be crucified?

119
00:08:53,890 --> 00:08:56,270
And that he would rise again the third day?

120
00:08:57,630 --> 00:08:59,430
And they remembered that he had said this.

121
00:08:59,810 --> 00:09:04,730
So they rushed back to tell his eleven disciples and everyone else what had happened.

122
00:09:05,190 --> 00:09:10,410
And the women who went to the tomb were Mary Magdalene, Joanna, Mary the mother of James, and several others.

123
00:09:10,670 --> 00:09:12,590
And they told the apostles what had happened.

124
00:09:12,850 --> 00:09:17,050
But the story sounded like nonsense, so they didn't believe it.

125
00:09:17,800 --> 00:09:23,420
However, Peter ran to the tomb to look, and stooping, he peered in and saw the empty linen wrappings,

126
00:09:23,420 --> 00:09:27,080
and he went home again, wondering what had happened.

127
00:09:29,690 --> 00:09:32,010
Friends, what do we do with these accounts?

128
00:09:32,830 --> 00:09:39,190
When we're challenged by people who say miracles cannot happen, contemporary science is all that there is,

129
00:09:39,390 --> 00:09:41,530
can we believe them? Can we believe these stories?

130
00:09:41,530 --> 00:09:45,190
Are they fantasy or are they truth and history?

131
00:09:47,600 --> 00:09:52,780
The German physicist Max Planck said this famous phrase.

132
00:09:52,940 --> 00:09:57,500
He said, faith in miracles must yield ground step by step

133
00:09:57,500 --> 00:10:02,350
before the steady and firm advance of the forces of science.

134
00:10:02,950 --> 00:10:07,550
And its total defeat is indubitably a mere matter of time.

135
00:10:08,530 --> 00:10:10,170
He has thrown down the gauntlet.

136
00:10:10,170 --> 00:10:14,170
He is saying that in time, science will prove everything miraculous.

137
00:10:14,890 --> 00:10:20,050
There is no need to step back and believe in a God that can do these things.

138
00:10:20,750 --> 00:10:22,130
So friends, I put it up here again.

139
00:10:22,130 --> 00:10:25,960
Is it rational to believe in miracles?

140
00:10:27,200 --> 00:10:27,860
Is it rational?

141
00:10:28,520 --> 00:10:32,820
Or are you an irrational individual caught up in myth and lore?

142
00:10:33,180 --> 00:10:34,120
I want to phrase it again.

143
00:10:34,360 --> 00:10:38,060
Is it rational for a mind that can build the hardware to split the atom?

144
00:10:38,360 --> 00:10:43,780
Is it rational for that kind of mind to believe in the supernatural or in miracles?

145
00:10:43,780 --> 00:10:49,780
Can I, as a critical thinker, embrace miracles as part of my worldview?

146
00:10:51,390 --> 00:10:54,670
The ancient Roman philosopher, Cicero, said this.

147
00:10:55,640 --> 00:10:58,560
He said, nothing happens without a cause.

148
00:10:59,810 --> 00:11:02,410
And nothing happens unless it can happen.

149
00:11:04,190 --> 00:11:08,790
When that which can happen does in fact happen, it cannot be considered a miracle.

150
00:11:10,040 --> 00:11:12,580
Hence, there are no miracles.

151
00:11:15,220 --> 00:11:15,640
Interesting.

152
00:11:17,180 --> 00:11:20,680
He's basically saying that a miracle is something that cannot happen.

153
00:11:20,800 --> 00:11:22,640
And so if something happens, it's not a miracle.

154
00:11:23,160 --> 00:11:28,000
That there must be some other normal, rational, scientific explanation.

155
00:11:28,440 --> 00:11:32,400
He wouldn't have used the term scientific, but the idea is if it can happen, it can happen.

156
00:11:33,040 --> 00:11:33,800
It's not a miracle.

157
00:11:34,830 --> 00:11:36,450
So what he's saying is don't go there.

158
00:11:36,850 --> 00:11:46,130
Dr. Norman Geisler summarizes the opposition position of Anthony Flew like this.

159
00:11:47,720 --> 00:11:51,360
Number one, miracles are by nature particular and unrepeatable.

160
00:11:53,170 --> 00:11:57,810
Number two, natural events are by nature general and repeatable.

161
00:11:59,160 --> 00:12:00,700
Therefore, number three, now in practice,

162
00:12:00,840 --> 00:12:03,460
the evidence for the general and repeatable is always greater

163
00:12:03,460 --> 00:12:05,960
than that for the particular and the unrepeatable.

164
00:12:06,820 --> 00:12:08,620
Number four, therefore, in practice,

165
00:12:08,620 --> 00:12:12,700
the evidence will always be greater against miracles than for them.

166
00:12:14,260 --> 00:12:16,900
These are different kinds of arguments around the same theme.

167
00:12:16,900 --> 00:12:21,860
Basically, these intellectual men are saying miracles simply cannot happen.

168
00:12:21,980 --> 00:12:23,220
There is an explanation.

169
00:12:23,720 --> 00:12:28,720
There's always a reason behind it that doesn't need a supernatural explanation.

170
00:12:29,120 --> 00:12:32,340
Those sound like strong arguments, don't they?

171
00:12:32,740 --> 00:12:36,600
And if we don't have an answer for that, it's easy for us to walk away and say,

172
00:12:36,680 --> 00:12:37,660
well, I'm not sure.

173
00:12:38,320 --> 00:12:41,100
And maybe in your own spirit, you're saying, I've always wondered about this.

174
00:12:41,180 --> 00:12:42,660
How do we reconcile these issues?

175
00:12:43,180 --> 00:12:47,840
And friends, there are people out there that will abandon their faith on these tenets

176
00:12:47,840 --> 00:12:52,270
and will walk away from worshiping God because of issues like this.

177
00:12:52,590 --> 00:12:54,550
So where do we go from here?

178
00:12:55,710 --> 00:12:58,130
Well, I want to say the crux of the matter is this.

179
00:12:58,530 --> 00:13:06,800
It comes down to the question of whether your worldview is going to allow for miracles or not.

180
00:13:07,620 --> 00:13:12,340
You see, your worldview is the lens through which you look at the world

181
00:13:12,340 --> 00:13:14,960
and you analyze what is happening around you.

182
00:13:15,380 --> 00:13:17,140
It's the view that you have

183
00:13:17,140 --> 00:13:19,440
that answers the questions that are around you.

184
00:13:19,700 --> 00:13:21,340
It can be shaped by science.

185
00:13:21,480 --> 00:13:22,780
It can be shaped by scripture.

186
00:13:23,200 --> 00:13:24,580
It can be shaped by philosophy.

187
00:13:25,020 --> 00:13:27,180
It can be shaped by a smorgasbord of ideas.

188
00:13:27,420 --> 00:13:29,340
But we all have a worldview.

189
00:13:29,760 --> 00:13:33,640
We interpret the world through our own lens in some way.

190
00:13:33,640 --> 00:13:36,040
We make sense of what happens around us

191
00:13:36,040 --> 00:13:39,040
in some fashion based on some principles.

192
00:13:40,190 --> 00:13:44,490
And if you have a preconceived idea that miracles cannot happen,

193
00:13:44,590 --> 00:13:46,870
that's the lens in which you view the world.

194
00:13:49,770 --> 00:13:52,190
If your preconceived worldview does not allow for miracles,

195
00:13:52,190 --> 00:13:55,230
as skeptics and even some Bible scholars will admit,

196
00:13:56,240 --> 00:13:59,680
then you will see miracle stories with a kind of a bias.

197
00:14:01,600 --> 00:14:02,260
I'll give you an example.

198
00:14:02,620 --> 00:14:05,940
If you're an atheistic skeptic, you don't believe there is a God at all,

199
00:14:06,140 --> 00:14:09,500
then you simply deny God's existence when you find a miracle story,

200
00:14:09,500 --> 00:14:12,840
and you deny the Bible as a record of the history of God and his people.

201
00:14:13,080 --> 00:14:17,460
You simply say, fable and lore, interesting, cute, and quaint,

202
00:14:18,550 --> 00:14:19,970
but not something to be believed.

203
00:14:21,490 --> 00:14:25,370
If you are a skeptical Bible scholar, and there are those out there,

204
00:14:26,060 --> 00:14:29,140
and you already preconceived that miracles don't exist,

205
00:14:29,620 --> 00:14:35,180
then you will interpret the miracle stories as perhaps exaggerated by the authors.

206
00:14:37,380 --> 00:14:40,440
Perhaps some other kind of natural phenomena took place

207
00:14:40,440 --> 00:14:43,440
that they didn't understand then, but we now know.

208
00:14:44,260 --> 00:14:46,980
And you can shift your interpretation in that way.

209
00:14:47,540 --> 00:14:50,410
Or, if your worldview allows,

210
00:14:50,490 --> 00:14:52,070
you can come to a miracle passage.

211
00:14:52,710 --> 00:14:54,490
And you can understand the authors

212
00:14:54,490 --> 00:14:55,850
are trying to communicate

213
00:14:55,850 --> 00:14:59,650
that God did something in that situation,

214
00:14:59,870 --> 00:15:03,450
outside of the natural, normal laws that we understand.

215
00:15:03,950 --> 00:15:05,110
And you then look to say,

216
00:15:05,190 --> 00:15:06,570
God, what are you trying to teach me?

217
00:15:07,170 --> 00:15:09,110
See, your worldview is very important.

218
00:15:09,110 --> 00:15:13,030
Does your worldview allow miracles to happen?

219
00:15:13,230 --> 00:15:14,110
So the question is rephrased.

220
00:15:14,950 --> 00:15:19,810
Is it rational to have a worldview that allows for miracles?

221
00:15:20,940 --> 00:15:23,080
And here's the summation of that question.

222
00:15:23,420 --> 00:15:26,800
Here is the bold and I would say very simple answer.

223
00:15:27,340 --> 00:15:28,740
And I put it up on the screen behind me.

224
00:15:29,340 --> 00:15:30,000
Here's the answer.

225
00:15:30,400 --> 00:15:38,480
If God exists, then it is rational to believe that miracles can happen.

226
00:15:39,820 --> 00:15:45,050
If God exists, then it's rational to believe miracles can happen.

227
00:15:46,720 --> 00:15:48,820
Dr. William Lane Craig sums it up very well.

228
00:15:49,700 --> 00:15:50,080
He writes,

229
00:15:50,180 --> 00:15:54,920
If there is a creator who designed and brought the universe into being

230
00:15:54,920 --> 00:15:57,440
and who sustains it moment by moment,

231
00:15:57,680 --> 00:16:02,140
who is responsible for the very laws of nature that govern the physical world,

232
00:16:02,140 --> 00:16:07,340
then certainly it's rational to believe that the miraculous is possible.

233
00:16:08,940 --> 00:16:09,860
Do you see how this works?

234
00:16:09,860 --> 00:16:17,680
If there is a God that set this whole thing up, it is rational to believe that it's possible he could do something different.

235
00:16:18,700 --> 00:16:20,720
So I want to come back to that definition of a miracle again.

236
00:16:21,040 --> 00:16:31,770
A miracle is, and it's up here on the screen, an event which is not producible by natural causes that are operative at the time and place the event occurs.

237
00:16:32,640 --> 00:16:34,040
Let's leave that up for a few moments.

238
00:16:37,110 --> 00:16:40,270
Friends, miracles lie outside the realm of science.

239
00:16:40,270 --> 00:16:42,530
And see, miracles don't contradict science.

240
00:16:42,830 --> 00:16:45,090
They simply are outside of it.

241
00:16:46,540 --> 00:16:48,820
Because the physical laws that we operate by,

242
00:16:49,790 --> 00:16:53,670
gravity, what holds us here to this earth,

243
00:16:54,900 --> 00:16:58,260
momentum, the physical laws we learn about,

244
00:16:58,400 --> 00:17:01,900
that some of us as engineers and scientists work with on a daily basis,

245
00:17:02,240 --> 00:17:04,700
all those laws have their own consistency.

246
00:17:05,120 --> 00:17:08,040
They operate over and over and over with regularity.

247
00:17:08,240 --> 00:17:10,380
But the underlying notion is this,

248
00:17:10,380 --> 00:17:13,580
that there's nothing else working upon them.

249
00:17:15,880 --> 00:17:18,440
You see, a miracle is not a violation of natural law.

250
00:17:19,160 --> 00:17:22,440
It's simply adding another variable to the equation.

251
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:26,380
J.P. Moreland from Talbot Seminary down the road

252
00:17:26,380 --> 00:17:29,160
gives an example about this issue.

253
00:17:30,220 --> 00:17:32,320
If you drop an object, it falls to earth.

254
00:17:33,270 --> 00:17:36,490
And it will do that over and over and over again.

255
00:17:36,990 --> 00:17:38,670
You can use the apple falling off a tree.

256
00:17:38,670 --> 00:17:40,690
It will fall over and over.

257
00:17:41,010 --> 00:17:41,710
That's the law.

258
00:17:41,710 --> 00:17:44,290
assuming nothing else is working on that apple.

259
00:17:44,470 --> 00:17:46,050
As gravity pulls it down to the earth,

260
00:17:46,110 --> 00:17:47,010
we can measure the speed,

261
00:17:47,090 --> 00:17:48,350
and it happens over and over and over.

262
00:17:48,690 --> 00:17:50,890
But you can, as a human being,

263
00:17:51,170 --> 00:17:53,630
intervene, stick your arm out, and catch it.

264
00:17:55,170 --> 00:17:57,310
You have not violated the law of gravity.

265
00:17:57,370 --> 00:17:58,670
You've simply intervened.

266
00:17:58,850 --> 00:18:00,990
You've added something else to the equation.

267
00:18:02,320 --> 00:18:04,480
It doesn't mean that gravity doesn't still happen.

268
00:18:04,540 --> 00:18:05,380
It doesn't mean that apples,

269
00:18:05,500 --> 00:18:07,120
when they fall off trees, don't hit the ground.

270
00:18:07,120 --> 00:18:08,780
But there's one more variable.

271
00:18:09,160 --> 00:18:10,640
You are there to intervene.

272
00:18:11,680 --> 00:18:13,040
You haven't contradicted the law.

273
00:18:13,220 --> 00:18:15,920
you simply added something else to it.

274
00:18:16,280 --> 00:18:17,980
And that is what I would like to argue

275
00:18:17,980 --> 00:18:19,780
is what happens when a miracle occurs.

276
00:18:20,160 --> 00:18:22,200
God doesn't overturn the laws of nature.

277
00:18:22,640 --> 00:18:24,880
God merely intervenes.

278
00:18:26,500 --> 00:18:27,740
So if there is a God,

279
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:30,480
then that scenario of a miracle

280
00:18:30,480 --> 00:18:33,120
is entirely rational and reasonable.

281
00:18:34,700 --> 00:18:35,700
For Brent's birthday,

282
00:18:36,580 --> 00:18:38,940
he got that classic game, Mousetrap.

283
00:18:39,300 --> 00:18:40,280
Do you know what I'm talking about?

284
00:18:40,860 --> 00:18:42,460
Back from the 70s, some of your kids,

285
00:18:42,500 --> 00:18:43,560
maybe you've played this game,

286
00:18:43,560 --> 00:19:04,920
And you build this little contraption where when it all goes at the end, you turn the crank that hits the boot, that knocks the ball, that goes down the little wiggle, that runs down the little corridor, hits the hand, drops another ball into the bathtub, which drops it onto a seesaw, flying the little man into the dish, whereby the trap comes down and catches the mouse.

287
00:19:05,940 --> 00:19:06,560
Did you follow that?

288
00:19:06,960 --> 00:19:08,260
You know what I'm talking about.

289
00:19:08,260 --> 00:19:19,590
From the perspective of the little plastic mouse, every time the crank is turned, all of these things happen and eventually the trap comes down.

290
00:19:21,260 --> 00:19:24,460
But Brent and I were having fun with trying different scenarios in this thing.

291
00:19:24,540 --> 00:19:32,280
We began to explore and there were times when he'd turn the crank and I would drop a ball earlier than was supposed to happen and we could disrupt the mechanism.

292
00:19:32,940 --> 00:19:39,420
Or I could simply withdraw a piece from the whole contraption and the trap would not come down.

293
00:19:39,420 --> 00:19:42,580
From the perspective of the mouse, a miracle has happened.

294
00:19:43,100 --> 00:19:46,180
Because he knows when you turn the crank and it goes to the boot and it goes to the ball and down and around,

295
00:19:46,320 --> 00:19:47,480
all these things take place.

296
00:19:47,840 --> 00:19:49,220
He knows it's going to happen.

297
00:19:49,580 --> 00:19:50,260
He's going to be caught.

298
00:19:50,520 --> 00:19:54,440
But I can, as somebody outside the game, I can simply intervene.

299
00:19:55,140 --> 00:19:56,520
I can just stop the production.

300
00:19:56,720 --> 00:19:57,840
Or I can speed it up.

301
00:19:58,420 --> 00:20:01,960
I can do all kinds of things to manipulate that game.

302
00:20:02,380 --> 00:20:04,580
I've not violated the game under normal circumstances.

303
00:20:05,120 --> 00:20:08,300
When you turn the crank and the boot goes and on and on and on, it always happens.

304
00:20:08,300 --> 00:20:10,120
But I can intervene.

305
00:20:11,110 --> 00:20:13,330
From the perspective of the mouse, I am God.

306
00:20:14,240 --> 00:20:16,180
And a miracle has happened.

307
00:20:18,860 --> 00:20:21,600
In a car engine, when the initial conditions are all the same,

308
00:20:21,720 --> 00:20:22,900
if you have everything hooked up right,

309
00:20:23,320 --> 00:20:26,440
the law is you turn the crank, the spark goes, and the engine turns over.

310
00:20:26,760 --> 00:20:28,600
But I can intervene and pull a plug.

311
00:20:29,930 --> 00:20:32,490
I can intervene and withdraw a spark plug.

312
00:20:32,730 --> 00:20:37,650
I can do things to disrupt the natural laws of a car motor.

313
00:20:38,010 --> 00:20:39,970
Have I violated the law of the car motor?

314
00:20:39,970 --> 00:20:45,770
No, Karmota still do those things, but I as an agent outside can intervene and do something

315
00:20:45,770 --> 00:20:50,450
different. Can you begin to see different examples that might come to mind of what it means to

316
00:20:50,450 --> 00:20:55,930
intervene in a system that under natural circumstances always goes to conclusion,

317
00:20:56,290 --> 00:21:02,840
but because another agent has come in there, you can change it and thereby produce a miracle.

318
00:21:05,440 --> 00:21:11,180
So the whole argument you can see rests on this issue. Does God exist? Because if God does exist,

319
00:21:11,180 --> 00:21:16,730
it's rational to believe that he could intervene and there could be miracles. See, once you accept

320
00:21:16,730 --> 00:21:22,110
that God exists, it's not a stretch to understand that he can do those kinds of things if he so

321
00:21:22,110 --> 00:21:26,350
chooses. But that last comment I just made is the crux of the matter for some people,

322
00:21:26,630 --> 00:21:35,250
if he so chooses. If God so chooses, perhaps some of you have asked for a miracle and nothing has

323
00:21:35,250 --> 00:21:41,690
happened. That's a particularly sensitive issue when it comes to the issue of healing and miracles.

324
00:21:42,730 --> 00:21:43,390
What do we do?

325
00:21:43,450 --> 00:21:46,710
We believe that God exists, and yet there is no healing.

326
00:21:48,160 --> 00:21:50,380
Now we've asked a whole different set of questions.

327
00:21:53,340 --> 00:21:57,200
Dr. Craig has asked that question by Lee Strobel in the book, if you've read it.

328
00:21:58,200 --> 00:22:00,640
It's a very poignant issue for Dr. Craig,

329
00:22:00,640 --> 00:22:05,240
because Dr. Craig has a congenital neuromuscular disease

330
00:22:05,240 --> 00:22:08,340
that causes atrophy in his extremities.

331
00:22:09,220 --> 00:22:11,860
So here is this great theologian, this great philosopher,

332
00:22:12,360 --> 00:22:15,120
Two PhDs, one in theology and one in philosophy.

333
00:22:15,200 --> 00:22:16,780
One of the greatest minds on the earth

334
00:22:16,780 --> 00:22:20,440
is suffering from a congenital neuromuscular disease

335
00:22:20,440 --> 00:22:23,540
that affects the limbs and they shake

336
00:22:23,540 --> 00:22:26,960
and they're not able to control things like others.

337
00:22:28,690 --> 00:22:30,290
And Strobel asked him this question.

338
00:22:31,320 --> 00:22:32,860
He basically asked him, Dr. Craig,

339
00:22:32,860 --> 00:22:34,780
if God loves you and has all the power,

340
00:22:35,160 --> 00:22:36,560
why haven't you been healed?

341
00:22:38,550 --> 00:22:40,890
And Dr. Craig says that though he had prayed for healing

342
00:22:40,890 --> 00:22:43,530
when he was younger, he doesn't pray for healing anymore.

343
00:22:43,870 --> 00:22:46,170
And listen to his answer, and I'm quoting it here.

344
00:22:46,950 --> 00:22:47,470
He writes,

345
00:22:47,470 --> 00:22:55,990
As I look at my life, God has used this disease in so many remarkable ways to shape me and my personality.

346
00:22:57,570 --> 00:22:57,930
He writes,

347
00:22:58,010 --> 00:23:04,460
Because I couldn't do athletics in order to succeed at something, I was driven into academics.

348
00:23:05,680 --> 00:23:09,740
I really owe my existence as a scholar to my having this disease.

349
00:23:10,700 --> 00:23:13,140
It's what compelled me to the life of the mind.

350
00:23:13,140 --> 00:23:20,450
and it also affected me psychologically giving me a tremendous drive to succeed and it caused me to

351
00:23:20,450 --> 00:23:25,250
have an achievement and a goal orientation which has helped me to do a lot in my life he says so

352
00:23:25,250 --> 00:23:30,890
I've really seen playing out in a very personal way what Paul said that his strength is made perfect

353
00:23:30,890 --> 00:23:38,120
in weakness just because you've asked for a miracle it doesn't mean that it will be granted

354
00:23:38,120 --> 00:23:45,150
a different topic for a different day but friends God is not a vending machine he is a person with

355
00:23:45,150 --> 00:23:49,150
choice and God has a larger perspective on our lives and the workings of the universe

356
00:23:49,150 --> 00:23:54,830
and can choose to do certain things and can choose not to and it's his prerogative and

357
00:23:54,830 --> 00:24:02,670
we need to let God be God and trust him knowing the Bible affirms he is still good even when

358
00:24:02,670 --> 00:24:04,990
there are things we don't understand happening around us.

359
00:24:09,180 --> 00:24:15,410
I want to now point to this final issue because this really is the crux now of the matter,

360
00:24:15,530 --> 00:24:16,910
why we should believe in God.

361
00:24:17,550 --> 00:24:21,390
To believe in miracles, we've argued, is rational if there's a God.

362
00:24:21,650 --> 00:24:24,450
So the original question about miracles is really this.

363
00:24:25,010 --> 00:24:26,390
It's not really about miracles.

364
00:24:26,650 --> 00:24:29,050
It's really about, is there a God at all?

365
00:24:29,960 --> 00:24:33,840
Because if there is, it's rational to believe that a miracle can happen.

366
00:24:33,840 --> 00:24:38,010
So how do we know, really, that there's a God?

367
00:24:39,990 --> 00:24:43,970
Dr. Craig, in his brilliance, lays out five evidences, and I want to share them with you.

368
00:24:45,200 --> 00:24:48,560
Here's why he argues we should believe in a miracle-working God.

369
00:24:48,860 --> 00:24:55,140
The first one is this, that God makes sense of the origins of the universe.

370
00:24:57,570 --> 00:25:01,550
You see, scientists across the board of different philosophical persuasions,

371
00:25:01,650 --> 00:25:03,130
different religions, and so forth,

372
00:25:03,130 --> 00:25:07,630
they will still tell us that at some point, time T in the past,

373
00:25:07,890 --> 00:25:09,430
that the universe had a beginning.

374
00:25:11,170 --> 00:25:14,030
In our experience, something does not come out of nothing.

375
00:25:14,850 --> 00:25:18,150
We argue there has to be a transcendent cause beyond space and time,

376
00:25:18,150 --> 00:25:23,330
that the universe is brought into being from a cause, from a causer.

377
00:25:23,910 --> 00:25:25,270
Craig's argument goes like this.

378
00:25:26,740 --> 00:25:29,440
Whatever begins to exist has a cause.

379
00:25:30,660 --> 00:25:33,290
The universe began to exist.

380
00:25:34,670 --> 00:25:37,480
Therefore, the universe has a cause.

381
00:25:39,460 --> 00:25:41,700
We'll call that cause God.

382
00:25:44,070 --> 00:25:48,830
That's actually the intro to next week's message on creation and evolution.

383
00:25:48,990 --> 00:25:51,350
I hope you'll come because we're going to tackle that one

384
00:25:51,350 --> 00:25:56,420
and really wrestle with the causes and the mechanisms for the universe.

385
00:25:58,660 --> 00:26:00,860
But I want to conclude with this point by saying that

386
00:26:00,860 --> 00:26:06,030
to understand the universe's origins,

387
00:26:07,540 --> 00:26:10,270
you've got to have a God to start it.

388
00:26:11,180 --> 00:26:11,980
So that's the first point.

389
00:26:12,020 --> 00:26:16,140
The second one is that God makes sense of the universe's complexity.

390
00:26:18,990 --> 00:26:19,810
Dr. Craig says,

391
00:26:19,810 --> 00:26:24,010
In the last 35 years, scientists have been stunned to discover

392
00:26:24,010 --> 00:26:28,020
that the Big Bang was not some chaotic primordial event,

393
00:26:28,280 --> 00:26:30,580
but rather a highly ordered event

394
00:26:30,580 --> 00:26:33,640
that required an enormous amount of information.

395
00:26:34,160 --> 00:26:36,040
In fact, from the very moment of its inception,

396
00:26:36,180 --> 00:26:38,240
the universe had to be fine-tuned

397
00:26:38,240 --> 00:26:40,240
to an incomprehensible precision

398
00:26:40,240 --> 00:26:43,660
for the existence of life like ourselves.

399
00:26:44,540 --> 00:26:46,980
And that points in a very compelling way, he says,

400
00:26:47,620 --> 00:26:50,300
toward the existence of an intelligent designer.

401
00:26:52,250 --> 00:26:54,430
Now, if you've got a scientific or a technical background,

402
00:26:54,430 --> 00:26:56,130
and I'm going to rattle off some facts

403
00:26:56,130 --> 00:26:57,750
that I think you'll find fascinating

404
00:26:57,750 --> 00:27:01,290
about how fine-tuned our universe is for life.

405
00:27:02,050 --> 00:27:04,810
British physicist P.C.W. Davies has concluded

406
00:27:04,810 --> 00:27:07,610
that the odds against the original conditions

407
00:27:07,610 --> 00:27:09,630
being suitable for the formation of stars,

408
00:27:10,450 --> 00:27:13,750
which are necessary for planets and then ultimately for life,

409
00:27:14,250 --> 00:27:18,130
is followed by at least 1,000 billion billion zeros.

410
00:27:19,720 --> 00:27:19,900
Wow.

411
00:27:22,390 --> 00:27:24,650
Davies also estimates that the strength of gravity

412
00:27:24,650 --> 00:27:26,990
or of the weak force at the atomic level.

413
00:27:27,310 --> 00:27:29,570
If it were changed, even one part in ten

414
00:27:29,570 --> 00:27:30,790
followed by a hundred zeros,

415
00:27:31,190 --> 00:27:32,950
life could never have developed.

416
00:27:35,270 --> 00:27:37,910
And also he says there are about 50 constants and quantities,

417
00:27:38,090 --> 00:27:40,230
for example, the amount of usable energy in the universe,

418
00:27:40,710 --> 00:27:43,790
the difference in mass between protons and neutrons,

419
00:27:43,790 --> 00:27:46,230
the rations of the fundamental forces of nature,

420
00:27:46,570 --> 00:27:48,430
and the proportion of matter to antimatter

421
00:27:48,430 --> 00:27:52,430
that must be balanced to a mathematically infinitesimal degree

422
00:27:52,430 --> 00:27:54,470
for any life to be possible.

423
00:27:54,890 --> 00:27:57,490
Friends, if we argue for a cosmic accident,

424
00:27:57,490 --> 00:27:59,490
we are not on solid ground.

425
00:28:01,250 --> 00:28:02,630
And more about that next week.

426
00:28:03,600 --> 00:28:04,520
If you want to read ahead, though,

427
00:28:04,600 --> 00:28:06,660
Dr. Hugh Ross's book, The Creator and the Cosmos,

428
00:28:06,900 --> 00:28:11,360
will lay out the physics and the realities of those issues.

429
00:28:13,120 --> 00:28:17,840
Number three, God makes sense of objective moral values.

430
00:28:18,480 --> 00:28:19,780
Now, we leave science for a moment,

431
00:28:19,840 --> 00:28:20,780
and we move into the humanities.

432
00:28:22,400 --> 00:28:23,720
And this argument goes like this.

433
00:28:23,760 --> 00:28:25,080
If God does not exist,

434
00:28:25,080 --> 00:28:28,960
then objective morals and values do not exist.

435
00:28:30,200 --> 00:28:33,020
No matter how much you want to argue for a utilitarian sense

436
00:28:33,020 --> 00:28:35,920
that morals are good for planet Earth,

437
00:28:36,120 --> 00:28:37,300
I would say yes they are,

438
00:28:37,460 --> 00:28:40,740
but you cannot prove that any one is truly better than the other.

439
00:28:41,180 --> 00:28:43,700
There's no objective sense of truth.

440
00:28:44,560 --> 00:28:45,780
Because if we're all an accident

441
00:28:45,780 --> 00:28:48,980
and there's no God who defines objective reality,

442
00:28:49,400 --> 00:28:52,640
then however you or I decide to concoct our morality

443
00:28:52,640 --> 00:28:54,100
is up to us.

444
00:28:54,100 --> 00:29:03,530
but you know what deep down when we get really honest when we really probe the depths of our

445
00:29:03,530 --> 00:29:11,980
own being we know that we don't live that way we know deep down that somewhere in our soul

446
00:29:11,980 --> 00:29:20,970
that child cruelty is just wrong it's just wrong objectively around the world in any culture

447
00:29:20,970 --> 00:29:23,550
that is just evil.

448
00:29:24,720 --> 00:29:25,800
And the challenge is,

449
00:29:25,940 --> 00:29:28,700
where do we get that sense of universal notion

450
00:29:28,700 --> 00:29:32,040
that something is cruel, evil, or wrong?

451
00:29:32,320 --> 00:29:34,020
Where does that come from?

452
00:29:34,420 --> 00:29:41,960
We know from our own experience

453
00:29:41,960 --> 00:29:45,520
that crashing airplanes into buildings

454
00:29:45,520 --> 00:29:48,100
is evil and wrong.

455
00:29:49,380 --> 00:29:50,220
Just know that.

456
00:29:52,310 --> 00:29:55,550
Where do we get the audacity to believe that

457
00:29:55,550 --> 00:29:58,830
if we are just an accident and there is no God?

458
00:29:59,130 --> 00:30:06,310
In fact, if there's no God, the challenge is, what is so special about human beings at all?

459
00:30:06,970 --> 00:30:11,130
If there's no God, then truly there isn't much difference between humans and animals,

460
00:30:11,370 --> 00:30:14,610
and we're justified then in living like animals.

461
00:30:16,770 --> 00:30:19,890
But if there's a God, the story's different.

462
00:30:21,060 --> 00:30:22,380
And friends, we don't live that way.

463
00:30:22,740 --> 00:30:27,740
Somehow, there's something across the board in humanity that wants to rise and live higher,

464
00:30:28,020 --> 00:30:30,140
and live moral and ethical lives.

465
00:30:30,140 --> 00:30:35,520
When funerals are given, we talk about transcendent qualities of personhood.

466
00:30:35,820 --> 00:30:41,140
We talk about goodness and the things that make us truly human, that rise above animals.

467
00:30:42,180 --> 00:30:44,460
Where do we get those notions if there's no God?

468
00:30:45,960 --> 00:30:47,460
There's no rational reason for it.

469
00:30:49,560 --> 00:30:55,440
God makes sense of the fact that we do agree there are objective moral values in our world.

470
00:30:57,310 --> 00:31:01,620
Number four, God makes sense of the resurrection.

471
00:31:03,610 --> 00:31:06,230
You see, the resurrection of Jesus Christ on Easter morning

472
00:31:06,230 --> 00:31:08,710
is one of those pivotal elements of the Christian faith.

473
00:31:09,310 --> 00:31:10,990
And the question is, why should we believe it?

474
00:31:12,180 --> 00:31:16,000
And there are four facts about that resurrection morning that,

475
00:31:16,700 --> 00:31:20,880
or rather the whole event of Jesus' crucifixion and resurrection,

